        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "What Adversarial Testing Means for Agents"
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Adversarial testing applies deliberate, hostile inputs to a system to find failures before an actual attacker does. For agentic systems the goal is not just to find inputs that cause bad "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "text",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": " output \u2014 it is to find inputs that trigger bad "
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "actions",
            "marks": [
              {
                "type": "italic"
              }
            ]
          },
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": ": wrong tool calls, unauthorised data access, policy violations, or multi-step escalation chains that individually look benign."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "paragraph",
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Three complementary techniques provide broad coverage: manual red-teaming (creative, open-ended), automated fuzzing (high volume), and property-based testing (formally specified invariants). Used together they catch different classes of failure."
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "type": "heading",
        "attrs": {
          "level": 2
        },
        "content": [
          {
            "type": "text",
            "text": "Technique Overview"
          }
        ]
      },
